mutant: m042_missing_block_arm_discards_siblings
target: internal/ingest/live/consumer.go
failure-mode: |
  The consumer's per-op-drop arm (DroppedOpsError: missing record
  blocks / spec-invalid op paths) advances the cursor and `continue`s
  instead of falling through to the append — silently discarding the
  WELL-FORMED sibling ops of the same commit along with the dropped
  one. A single partial-CAR commit from a non-canonical PDS (the
  production shape that motivated the arm) then costs every record it
  carried, not just the block-less op: permanent, metric-invisible
  data loss that the drop counters actively mask (they report exactly
  the drops the operator expects to see).
expected-detection: |
  frames tier: TestOracle_FrameStrippedLeafBlockDropsOp drives the real
  consumer over a simulator commit whose CAR omits one record leaf
  block among three create ops and barriers on the surviving siblings'
  durable rows — under this mutant the siblings never land and the
  waitForRowCount barrier times out ("timed out waiting for the
  surviving sibling rows"). The live-package unit test
  TestProcessBatch_MissingBlockOpDoesNotShutDownConsumer kills faster
  and directly: its WriterMetrics.EventsAppended assertion ("the
  surviving sibling op must be archived, not discarded with the
  dropped one") reads 0 instead of 1.
expected-tier: frames
tiers: frames

